In 3.13 the filter dropdown would show all my filters, which was fine as I could select the one I wanted.

In 4.0 the 'Issues' dropdown shows a section titled "Favourite Filters" - but this isn't showing the ones that are actually my favourites, as in the ones I want to use most often. They are simply the first 10 alphabetically.

To access the ones I use most often (which are generally starting with 'QA...' then I must click on 'more', wait for the page to load, then click the one I want. This is annoying. Shouldn't JIRA be able to work out which filters I use the most?

Multiple email subscriptions will be sent from the first users locale.

In the IssueWebTableComponent we pass in an I18nBean gotten from the JiraAuthenticationContex.

This is its implementation:

{code:java}
    public I18nBean getI18nBean()
    {
        I18nBean i18nBean = (I18nBean) getRequestCache().get(RequestCacheKeys.I18N_BEAN);
        if (i18nBean == null)
        {
            i18nBean = new I18nBean(getUser());
            getRequestCache().put(RequestCacheKeys.I18N_BEAN, i18nBean);
        }
        return i18nBean;
    }
{code}

We need to generate a new I18nBean for each subscription.

Converted query looks like this:
{{affectedVersion = unreleasedVersions()}}
instead of this:
{{affectedVersion in unreleasedVersions()}}

Same for releasedVersions flag, as well as the issue type flags (all standard, all sub task).

{quote}
Find all issues whose Summary contains a word beginning with "fin":
{quote}
This is not exactly true - it uses Lucene stemming.
So something like this would be more correct:
{quote}
Find all issues whose Summary contains the word "run" (or derivatives of that word like "running" or "ran").
{quote}

Also we need to mention that we will not be able to find word parts, instead our text search does whole word searching.

Perhaps we need to make it more clear that this is all really dictated by the Lucene Query parser and that you need to understand what that is doing to understand how JIRA text fields are being searched.

